-- Proof Factoring (CredTT-Native #6)
--
-- NEW: Isolate low-credence steps from high-credence core
-- Keep the stable part separate from the weak part
--
-- Example: Factor proof into "definitely true" core + "probably true" fringe

-- Classical: all steps equal, no factoring possible
-- CredTT: separate high-c steps from low-c steps

-- HIGH-CREDENCE CORE: steps at c = 1
-- These are the DEFINITELY true parts
-- Mathematical theorems, verified computations

postulate axiom1 : A1 @ 1
postulate axiom2 : A2 @ 1
postulate theorem : T @ 1

-- Core is stable: 1 * 1 * 1 = 1
stable axiom1
stable axiom2
stable theorem

-- LOW-CREDENCE FRINGE: steps at c < 1
-- These are the PROBABLY true parts
-- Empirical assumptions, unverified claims

postulate assumption : B1 @ 8/10
postulate conjecture : B2 @ 7/10

-- Fringe has lower credence: 0.8 * 0.7 = 0.56

-- FACTORED PROOF:
-- Core |- C @ 1 (stable, certain)
-- Fringe + Core |- D @ 0.56 * 1 = 0.56 (less certain)

-- Why factoring matters:
-- 1. Identify what's definitely true vs probably true
-- 2. If fringe fails, core is still valid
-- 3. Prioritize verification of fringe

-- Example: Physics proof
-- Core: mathematical derivation @ 1
-- Fringe: empirical assumptions @ 0.9
-- Result @ 0.9 (limited by fringe)

-- If fringe is invalidated:
-- Core remains valid
-- Just need new fringe assumptions

-- MODULAR CREDENCE:
-- Factor proof into modules
-- Each module has own credence
-- Combining: product of credences

-- Module A @ 0.95
-- Module B @ 0.90
-- Module C @ 0.85
-- Combined @ 0.95 * 0.90 * 0.85 = 0.73

-- This is like dependency analysis for credence
-- Know which modules contribute most uncertainty
